{{Social teachings of the popes}}
'''''Dignitatis humanae''''' ({{lang-la|Of the Dignity of the Human Person}}{{efn|The document is known by its ''[[incipit]]'', the first words of the document in the original [[Latin]] text, as is customary for similar [[Catholic Church]] documents.}}) is the [[Second Vatican Council]]'s '''Declaration on Religious Freedom'''.&lt;ref&gt;The full text of a translation into English is available from the [https://www.vatican.va/archive/hist_councils/ii_vatican_council/documents/vat-ii_decl_19651207_dignitatis-humanae_en.html Holy See's website] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120211202206/https://www.vatican.va/archive/hist_councils/ii_vatican_council/documents/vat-ii_decl_19651207_dignitatis-humanae_en.html |date=February 11, 2012 }}&lt;/ref&gt; In the context of the council's stated intention &quot;to develop the doctrine of recent popes on the inviolable rights of the human person and the constitutional order of society&quot;, ''Dignitatis humanae'' spells out the church's support for the protection of religious liberty. It set the ground rules by which the church would relate to secular states, and in effect repudiated the traditional principle that &quot;[[error has no rights]]&quot;, i.e., that non-Catholics did not deserve civil or political rights.

The passage of this measure by a vote of 2,308 to 70 is considered by many to be one of the most significant events of the council.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;Thus, during the final vote on the morning of December 7 (when the fathers had to choose between a simple approval or disapproval of the last draft), Lefebvre was one of the 70&amp;nbsp;— about 3 percent of the total&amp;nbsp;— who voted against the schema.&quot; [http://www.catholicculture.org/docs/doc_view.cfm?recnum=857 Marcel Lefebvre: Signatory to ''Dignitatis humanae''], by Brian Harrison&lt;/ref&gt; This declaration was promulgated by Pope Paul VI on December 7, 1965.

''Dignitatis humanae'' became one of the key points of dispute between the Vatican and traditionalists such as Archbishop [[Marcel Lefebvre]] who argued that the council document was incompatible with previous authoritatively stated Catholic teaching.

==Background==

===Earlier Catholic view===
{{further|Modernism in the Catholic Church}}

Historically, the ideal of Catholic political organization was a tightly interwoven structure of the Catholic Church and secular rulers generally known as [[Christendom]], with the Catholic Church having a favoured place in the political structure.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book|title = A Concise History of the Catholic Church|last = Bokenkotter|first = Thomas J|publisher = Doubleday|year = 2004|isbn = |location = New York|pages = }}&lt;/ref&gt; In 1520, [[Pope Leo X]] in the papal bull ''[[Exsurge Domine]]'' had condemned the proposition &quot;That heretics be burned is against the will of the Spirit&quot; as one of a number of errors that were &quot;destructive, pernicious, scandalous, and seductive to pious and simple minds&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|last1=Swinburne|first1=Richard|title=Revelation: From Metaphor to Analogy|date=1992|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780191519529|pages=216|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yhEAPsPQbMUC&amp;pg=PA216|language=en}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|last1=Beinert|first1=Wolfgang|title=Verbindliches Zeugnis|date=1992|publisher=Vandenhoeck &amp; Ruprecht|isbn=9783451236259|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3FPssCvqPkoC&amp;pg=PA196|language=de}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|last1=Hoose|first1=Bernard|title=Received Wisdom?: Reviewing the Role of Tradition in Christian Ethics|date=1994|publisher=Geoffrey Chapman|isbn=9780225667394|pages=21|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0gfXAAAAMAAJ|language=en}}&lt;/ref&gt;

This ideal was challenged by the [[Protestant Reformation]], the rise of [[nation-states]] and [[the Enlightenment]]. The [[French Revolution]], the failed radical [[Revolutions of 1848]] and the loss of the [[Papal States]] traumatized many Catholic leaders, who held on to traditional ideas of relations with the secular powers.

[[Pope Pius IX]] had condemned the idea of abstract religious freedom. [[Pope Leo XIII]], who had established working relationships with both the French and German secular statesmen, issued the bull ''[[Testem benevolentiae nostrae]]'' against the [[Americanism (heresy)|Americanist heresy]], alleged by some to be a specifically European problem wherein the attempt was made to apply democratic concepts and American models of church–state relations to Catholic Church governance in Europe.

====The Spanish model====
The result was that as of the mid-20th century, an example of Catholic church–state relations was the Catholic situation in [[Spain under Franco|Spain]] (''nacionalcatolicismo''), where the Catholic Church:
*was officially recognized and protected by the state,
*had substantial control over social policy, and
*had this relationship explicitly set out in a [[concordat]].
It had long been the policy of the Catholic Church to support [[toleration]] of competing religions under such a scheme, but to support legal restrictions on attempts to convert Catholics to those religions.

===John Courtney Murray===

The Spanish approach to church–state relations was problematic for many [[Roman Catholicism in the United States|American Catholics]]. By the mid-20th century, the Catholic Church in the United States had managed to overcome much of the deeply held anti-Catholic belief that marked the [[Nativism (politics)|nativist]] movements of the 19th century, partly fuelled by concerns about church–state separation. The prohibition of the establishment of a state church, required by the Bill of Rights, had allowed the construction of an extensive network of Catholic educational, health-care and social service institutions. But some, following the view of the influential priest and economist [[John A. Ryan]], believed that established Catholic teachings conflicted with the American experience of religious freedom, holding that if Catholics ever became the majority group, they would be bound to enact, if possible, the kind of church–state relationship that existed in countries such as Spain.{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}} The arrangements in the United States were permissible only as long as the other model was not politically feasible.{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}}

By the early 1940s, however, the Jesuit theologian [[John Courtney Murray]] perceived that the most important coming challenge was [[secularism]], a challenge that could best be confronted by many faith communities working together. The American view of separate church and state led to understandable mistrust of the motives of a quickly growing American Catholic community. Murray began to develop a view based on the American experience, where a government limited by law protects the liberty of all religious communities equally, while the church pursues its aims by exercising its influence in society in general, without relying on government intervention to enforce the church's beliefs.&lt;!--this can be made more accurate--&gt; This view was developed in a series of articles in such Catholic journals as ''America'', while Joseph Fenton,&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.acton.org/publicat/books/liberty/hmention1.html John Courtney Murray and the American Catholic Experience] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060525104724/http://www.acton.org/publicat/books/liberty/hmention1.html |date=2006-05-25 }} by Michael Tortolani, [[Acton Institute]]&lt;/ref&gt; as editor of the ''American Ecclesiastical Review,'' defended the traditional view and asserted that Murray's views contradicted essential Catholic teachings. In 1954 Murray's ideas were censored by the Secretary of the [[Congregation for the Doctrine of the Faith|Holy Office]] and he ceased publishing works on this specific topic until his vindication by Vatican II.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=https://novusordowatch.org/2013/04/murray-religious-liberty-vatican2/|title=John Courtney Murray's Religious Liberty Error is Doctrine of Vatican II|date=2013-04-01|website=Novus Ordo Watch|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-30}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Vatican II and religious freedom==

===Preparation and first session (1962)===
The initial conflict was regarding just what model of religious freedom was to be put before the council, with the traditionalists calling for religious tolerance but claiming that an abstract right to religious liberty was [[relativist]]ic.&lt;ref name=&quot;sspx.org&quot;&gt;{{Cite web |url=http://www.sspx.org/archbishop_lefebvre/ab_lefebvre_preparing_the_council.htm |title=Archbishop Lefebvre Preparing the Council |access-date=2011-04-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111010215803/http://www.sspx.org/archbishop_lefebvre/ab_lefebvre_preparing_the_council.htm |archive-date=2011-10-10 |url-status=dead }}&lt;/ref&gt; Before the council both the [[Pontifical Council for Promoting Christian Unity]] led by Cardinal [[Augustin Bea]]{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}} and the Theological Commission (led by Cardinal [[Alfredo Ottaviani]]){{Citation needed|date=February 2007}} introduced revised drafts of statements to the Central Commission. Pope John XXIII in July appointed an ad hoc joint committee to resolve differences and Bea's &quot;Unity&quot; submitted a revised draft. Negotiations between the various commissions broke down after this point.{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}}

The first session concentrated mainly on [[liturgy]] and on the nature of the church. A declaration on religious freedom, largely drawn from the &quot;Unity&quot; draft, was made part (chapter V) of the schema on [[Ecumenism]]; the bishops did not have time to get to it. On January 13, after the close of the first session, Bea indicated at a talk at [[Pro Deo University]] in Rome that he intended to prepare a constitution on human freedom for the next session, to make sure the issue would not go away.
